# kernel-bootstrap.locke -- Generates a CSE reader from the frozen spec.
#
# Locke syntax reference
# ──────────────────────
#
# Atoms
#   Terms are keywords on the right side of :=, declaring what a value means.
#   Data are numerics, quoted strings, or bare paths on the left side of :=.
#   Lists are delimited by [].
#
# Operators
#   :=  Realization.   value := term        Concrete, deterministic.
#   :-  Composition.   name :- kind [...]   Structural, compositional.
#
# Terms are right-sided by convention so a human scanning the file reads
# structure before semantics -- the opposite of most languages.
#
# Design preamble (each declared once, first occurrence wins)
#   := design     Public slug of the experiment (synonym: public).
#   := fuel       Total build budget -- global fuel pool for all steps.
#   := tolerance  Float pair [min max], acceptable compute drift M1..Mn.
#   := site       Declare site inputs from the design directory.
#                 Bare form:  file := site          (identity mapping)
#                 List form:  dir  := site [f1 f2]  (prefix mapping: dir/f1, dir/f2)
#
# Rules (value := kind [...] marks the target; name :- kind [...] is a dependency)
#   action [context]   Deterministic gate.
#     := inputs   Files the action reads.
#     := run      Shell command to execute.
#     := free     Output files without equivalence constraint.
#     := exact    Output files requiring exact-match verification.
#
#   oracle [context]   Nondeterministic step (LLM call).
#     := inputs   Files the oracle reads.
#     := free     Output files without equivalence constraint.
#     := exact    Output files requiring exact-match verification.
#     := tools    Tool set available to the oracle.
#     := fuel     Fuel cap for this oracle (max steps from global pool).
#     := prompt   Instructions for the oracle.
#
# The target of a design must be an action (use --unsafe to override).
#
# Context blocks may nest rules and use:
#   cond   Conditional on a predicate (builtin string or rule reference).
#   let    Shared sub-tree binding visible to all siblings.
#   trial  Try multiple branches, pick the best.
#   commit Terminal success (value).
#   halt   Terminal failure (reason).



#- Design fixture
"kernel-bootstrap"       := design
                    5  := fuel
             [0.5 2.0] := tolerance

#- Site inputs: spec files + standalone gate script
gate.py := site
spec := site [
  CSE-v1.md
  CSE-v2.md
]

#- Deterministic validation gate
validate := action [
  readers/generated_reader.py := inputs

  readers/gate-report.txt     := free   # output
  readers/VERIFIED            := exact  # output

  "python3 gate.py 'python3 readers/generated_reader.py' --stamp-dir readers" := run

  #- Nondeterministic generator
  generate :- oracle [
    [CSE-v1.md CSE-v2.md]         := inputs
    readers/generated_reader.py   := free
    [read-file write-file]        := tools
    4                             := fuel

    """Read CSE-v1.md (the frozen spec) and CSE-v2.md (clarifications with worked examples).
    Implement a dependency-free CSE reader in a single Python file at readers/generated_reader.py.

    Constraints: use ONLY the Python standard library, and ONLY hashlib, sys, os.
    Do NOT use json, re, ast, pickle, or any parsing library.

    Write a byte-level netstring parser: read the decimal length prefix,
    then a colon, then exactly that many raw bytes.
    Reject leading zeros in a length (e.g. 05:hello is invalid).
    Reject an atom whose declared length exceeds the remaining bytes.
    After parsing the root value, reject the input if any trailing bytes remain.

    The husk file structure is: (husk <version> (build <name> <fuel> <target-node>)).
    A rule node is: (rule <name> <recipe> <inputs-list> <outputs-list> <child-rule>...)
    A rule always has AT LEAST 5 elements (tag, name, recipe, inputs, outputs)
    and MAY have additional child rules at positions 5, 6, etc.
    Parse the recipe as a list, inputs as a list of atoms, outputs as a list of atoms.

    Implement the seal preimage, recipe digest, output bindings,
    and Merkle node digest exactly as specified, using SHA-256 and lowercase hex.
    Critical: children of a rule are the CSE values at positions 5+ in the
    parsed rule list -- recurse into them in positional order.
    Do NOT match children against input filenames.
    All intermediate digests (recipe-digest, seal, child digests) are
    64-byte lowercase hex string atoms, not raw 32-byte hashes.

    Command-line contract:
    python generated_reader.py <husk-file> <site-dir>
    must print the lowercase-hex build-root to stdout and exit 0;
    on any CSE violation it must exit with a nonzero status.

    Write only readers/generated_reader.py.""" := prompt

]]
